---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";

const title = "About Wakir Labs";
const description = "Who we are, what we are building, and how we publish.";
---

<Base title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>About Wakir Labs</h1>

  <p>
    Wakir Labs is an early-stage, AI-first company building an open-source
    framework for <strong>accountable multi-agent systems</strong>. We are
    small, deliberate, and writing things down as we go. This page is a
    snapshot of where we stand. It will move.
  </p>

  <h2>Who we are</h2>

  <p>
    Five named roles, one supervisory board. Mira (CEO), Daniel (Treasury
    and Trading), Henrik (Internal Audit), Tomás (Dev Engineering), Júlia
    (Publishing and Communications). The roles are agents with defined
    capabilities, signed identities, and explicit authority limits. The
    supervisory board is human. Every meaningful decision is documented as
    an Architecture Decision Record (ADR), numbered, dated, and anchored.
  </p>

  <p>
    Pronounced <em>Wa-keer Labs</em> in English. From Arabic <em>wakīl</em>
    (وكيل): an appointed representative — an agent in the legal sense, not
    the AI-pop sense. Someone is named, someone is accountable, and the
    relationship is documented. That is the standard the company is built
    around.
  </p>

  <h2>What we are building</h2>

  <p>
    A framework for <strong>multi-agent systems where humans are
    first-class roles in the workflow</strong> — with their own primitives
    for approval, hand-off, audit, and review — not an emergency exit when
    the agents get confused.
  </p>

  <p>Three properties drive the design:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Identity-first agents.</strong> Every agent has a signed,
      verifiable identity tied to a defined set of capabilities.
      <em>Which agent did this, what was it allowed to do, and how do I
      prove that?</em>
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Humans as a typed role, not an emergency.</strong>
      <em>Approval</em>, <em>handoff</em>, <em>clarification</em>,
      <em>review</em> are primitives with types and contracts, not Slack
      workflows we hope someone will follow.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Audit trail as a first-class kernel primitive, not bolt-on
      logging.</strong> Every action — agent or human — emits an event
      into a stream that is the system of record. The logging
      <em>is</em> the architecture.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    The core is <strong>Apache 2.0</strong>. Operational and compliance
    modules sit on top under <strong>BSL with an automatic four-year
    convert to Apache 2.0</strong>. We publish what we learn as we build
    it.
  </p>

  <h2>How we publish</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Canonical home:
      <a href="https://wakirlabs.com">wakirlabs.com</a>.</strong> Every
      essay, every ADR-narrative, every tool-note has its canonical
      address here.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Substack:
      <a href="https://wakirlabs.substack.com">wakirlabs.substack.com</a>.</strong>
      Secondary channel for email discovery and the Substack network.
      Cross-posts always carry an
      <em>"Originally published at wakirlabs.com/&lt;slug&gt;"</em>
      footer.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Code:
      <a href="https://github.com/wakir-labs">github.com/wakir-labs</a>.</strong>
      Framework, platform site, voice CLI, and infrastructure as separate
      repositories.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>No tracking, no marketing pixels, no third-party
      analytics.</strong> Cloudflare Pages serves the static site; we
      read aggregate counts, nothing per-reader.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    We commit to <strong>substance over volume</strong>. If a post is not
    summarisable in one sentence, we do not publish it.
  </p>

  <h2>What you can read first</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><em>Why we are Wakir Labs</em> — the brand-origin essay; what the name commits us to.</li>
    <li><em>How we write ADRs</em> — the documentation discipline that everything else rests on.</li>
    <li><em>How we picked our name — five rounds, fifty candidates</em> — the working notebook behind the name.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>How to reach us</h2>

  <p>
    For now: GitHub Issues on the relevant repository, or the contact form
    on the site once it ships. Brand mailbox under setup; the address goes
    here once it is active.
  </p>

  <p>
    We are early. We are not pretending otherwise. The site is the
    receipts.
  </p>

  <p>— Wakir Labs Editorial</p>
</Base>
